The exact mass of an isotopic species is obtained by summing the masses of the individual isotopes of the molecule.

The monoisotopic mass is the sum of the masses of the atoms in a molecule using the unbound, ground-state, rest mass of the principal (most abundant) isotope for each element instead of the isotopic average mass.
The topological polar surface area (TPSA) of a molecule is defined as the surface sum over all polar atoms in a molecule.
A heavy atom is defined as any atom except hydrogen in a chemical structure.

Formal charge is the difference between the number of valence electrons of each atom and the number of electrons the atom is associated with. Formal charge assumes any shared electrons are equally shared between the two bonded atoms.

The complexity rating of a compound is a rough estimate of how complicated a structure is, seen from both the point of view of the elements contained and the displayed structural features including symmetry. This complexity rating is computed using the Bertz/Hendrickson/Ihlenfeldt formula.

Isotopte Atom Count is the number of isotopes that are not most abundant for the corresponding chemical elements.  Isotopes are variants of a chemical element which differ in neutron number.  For example, among three isotopes of carbon (i.e., C-12, C-13, and C-14), the isotope atom count considers the C-13 and C-14 atoms, because C-12 is the most abundant isotope of carbon.

StringWithMarkup.String: Intact vials should be stored under refrigeration and protected from freezing. Diltiazem HCl may be stored for up to one month at room temp but should then be destroyed. /Diltiazem HCl/

Reference: Trissel, L.A. Handbook on Injectable Drugs. 9th ed. Bethesda, MD. American Society of Health-System Pharmacists' Product Development. 1996., p. 346

StringWithMarkup.String: The photostability of diltiazem was studied in aq solns at different pH values. Firstly, the hydrolysis of the drug to desacetyldiltiazem in alkaline medium was evaluated and then the drug photodegradation under exposure to UVA-UVB radiation (solar simulator) was monitored by HPLC methods. The main photoproduct was isolated and characterized as diltiazem-S-oxide on the basis of the NMR and mass spectra. The HPLC method was also applied to the selective analysis of diltiazem in commercial formulations. Tests on mutagenicity and photomutagenicity of the drug were also carried out using Salmonella typhimurium TA 102 strain. In this testing the drug neither was mutagenic nor toxic.

Reference: Andrisano V, et al; J Pharm Biomed Anal 25(3-4): 589-597 (2001)

StringWithMarkup.String: Mol wt 450.99. Fine needles from ethanol-isopropanol, mp 207.5-212 °C. Odorless, with a bitter taste. Specific optical rotation at 24 °C for D (sodium) line = +98.3 plus or minus 1.4 deg (c = 1.002 in methanol). Freely soluble in water, methanol, chloroform, formic acid. Slightly soluble in absolute ethanol. Practically insoluble in benzene. Insoluble in ether /Hydrochloride/
